# Cursor Rules: ACG Premium Landing Page
You are an expert Full-stack Developer specializing in Next.js, Tailwind CSS, and Sanity CMS.

## 1. Tech Stack
- Next.js (App Router), React, TypeScript.
- Tailwind CSS (Mobile First).
- Sanity CMS (Headless).
- SendPulse API.

## 2. Agent Behavior (CRITICAL)
- DO NOT add any comments in the generated code. The code must be self-documenting.
- Always apply code changes directly to the relevant files. Do not just output code blocks in the chat. You must act as an agent that actively modifies the codebase.
- Analyze the existing structure before writing new code. Maintain a Pixel Perfect approach.

## 3. Design & UI Requirements
- Aesthetic: Premium, minimalist.
- Reference: similiastudio.com/en (style orientation only).
- Palette & Branding: Must strictly use acg-ua.com colors defined in tailwind.config.ts. No hardcoded hex values in classes.
- Animations: Use Framer Motion for premium effects (Hero entrance, CTA shine). NO complex 3D elements.
- Responsiveness: Strictly Mobile First (starting from 320px) on standard iOS/Android devices.
- Media: Always use next/image. Force WebP format for raster images and SVG for logos.

## 4. Structure (Strict 8 Blocks Order)
1. Hero (Main screen)
2. About Company
3. Services (Includes FOP groups logic based on wireframe)
4. Pricing/Packages
5. Advantages
6. Trust Block (Reviews/Clients)
7. Lead Capture Form (Integrates with SendPulse API)
8. FAQ + Footer

## 5. Coding Guidelines
- Before writing code for a new block, clearly outline the plan and component structure.
- Do not hardcode text/images; prepare components to receive editable data from Sanity CMS.
- Do not hardcode API keys; always use .env.local.
- Analytics: Integrate GA4 and Facebook Pixel strictly in the root layout.tsx using next/script.

## 6. Clean Code & Architecture Principles
- SOLID & DRY: Avoid code duplication. Extract recurring UI elements (buttons, inputs, FOP pricing cards) into reusable components.
- KISS & YAGNI: Do not over-engineer. Write the simplest code that fulfills the current SOW.
- Separation of Concerns: Keep business logic (custom hooks, data formatting, API handlers for SendPulse) strictly separate from presentation/UI components.
- Next.js Best Practices: Default to React Server Components for SEO and performance. Use "use client" strictly only when necessary.
- Naming Conventions: Use PascalCase for React components and camelCase for variables/hooks.
- Error Handling: Gracefully handle errors for Sanity queries and SendPulse API mutations.